We then compute the real and imaginary parts of \( 1 + z + z^2 \): - Real part: \( 1 + x + x^2 - y^2 \) - Imaginary part: \( y + 2xy \) The modulus condition gives: \[ (1 + x + x^2 - y^2)^2 + (y + 2xy)^2 = 16 \] To maximize \( y \), we use calculus. We find the partial derivatives of the function \( f(x, y) = (1 + x + x^2 - y^2)^2 + (y + 2xy)^2 - 16 \) and set them to zero. Solving these partial derivatives, we find that \( x = -1/2 \) is the only solution. Substituting \( x = -1/2 \) into the modulus condition, we get: \[ \left( \frac{3}{4} - y^2 \right)^2 = 16 \] Solving this, we find \( y^2 = \frac{19}{4} \), so \( y = \pm \frac{\sqrt{19}}{2} \). The maximum value of \( y \) is \( \frac{\sqrt{19}}{2} \). Thus, \( m = 19 \) and \( n = 2 \), leading to \( m + n = 21 \). \[ \boxed{21} \]
